FIRE destroyed 97 shacks at Jika Joe squatter camp in Pietermaritzburg in KZN midlands. It is alleged that this fire that broke out in the middle of Saturday night and affected 164 people.  Earlier today (Sunday), KZN acting premier, Ravi Pillay who was accompanied by the Msunduzi mayor, Mzimkhulu Thebolla and other senior officials from the Department of Cooperative Governance and Traditional Affairs (COGTA) visited the victims of the shack fire. Addressing the victims of fire, Pillay said it was saddening to see that just when the province is recovering from terrible weather conditions that devastated the province in October and November. “We are saddened by what we see before us today and we feel for the families that had to go through the traumatic experience of losing their belongings. We are thankful to the Almighty that there were no injuries or deaths in this fire," said Pillay.      He revealed that the victims of fire were moved into a temporary shelter at one of the community halls close to the area. "We are thankful for the ongoing support that is coming from the non-governmental sector as we continue to provide interim relief to the affected people,” said Pillay.  Pillay revealed that he has tasked the Cooperative Governance and Traditional Affairs MEC, Peggy Nkonyeni to coordinate the provision of relief that will be provided by the relevant provincial departments. 